      <p>The bass player is the ultimate 'harmonic judge.' When you play a C major chord on your guitar, the listener hears it as C major because the bass is (usually) playing the 'root' note, C. But if the bass moves to an A, that same C major chord suddenly sounds like an Am7. The bass has the power to redefine the entire harmonic identity of a progression. We offer 'Low-End Theory Modules' that show you how to navigate these relationships, teaching you how to 'lock-in' with your bassist to create a unified harmonic front. Understanding 'Inversions' and 'Slash Chords' from a bass perspective will change how you write and arrange your own guitar parts forever.</p>

